<emphasis id="04C6EA90FFF5031CFFDA2A3954DD664C" bold="true" box="[114,188,1088,1102]" pageId="1" pageNumber="221">Figs 1–3.</emphasis>
Host plant, 
<taxonomicName id="F1B24D01FFF5031CFE8A2A4655D6664C" authority="A. Juss." authorityName="A. Juss." box="[290,439,1087,1102]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malpighiaceae" genus="Pterandra" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="221" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pyroidea">
<emphasis id="04C6EA90FFF5031CFE8A2A465519664C" box="[290,376,1087,1102]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="221">P. pyroidea</emphasis>
A. Juss.
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="F1B24D01FFF5031CFE682A39565B664C" authorityName="de Jussieu" authorityYear="1789" box="[448,570,1088,1102]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malpighiaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="221" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Malpighiaceae</taxonomicName>
). 1. General aspect. 2. Galled leaf (galls induced by 
<taxonomicName id="F1B24D01FFF5031CFC7F2A4650C8664C" authority="Maia &amp; Flor" authorityName="Maia &amp; Flor" authorityYear="2018" box="[983,1193,1087,1102]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Myrciamyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="221" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pterandrae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="04C6EA90FFF5031CFC7F2A465024664C" box="[983,1093,1087,1102]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="221">M. pterandrae</emphasis>
Maia &amp; Flor
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="1FF557EBFFF5031CFB182A395090664C" box="[1200,1265,1088,1102]" pageId="1" pageNumber="221" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
). 3. Plant reaction against the gall induction.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="360D3682FFF5031CFF3A2ACE55E067C7" blockId="1.[114,785,1151,1477]" pageId="1" pageNumber="221">
Plant reactions against the galler attack were observed and photographed (
<figureCitation id="AE892A07FFF5031CFEBD2AAA552E66E4" box="[277,335,1235,1254]" captionStart="Figs 1–3" captionStartId="1.[114,148,1088,1102]" captionTargetBox="[423,1193,153,1063]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[423,1192,186,1058]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figs 1–3. Host plant, P. pyroidea A. Juss. (Malpighiaceae). 1. General aspect. 2. Galled leaf (galls induced by M. pterandrae Maia &amp; Flor, sp. nov.). 3. Plant reaction against the gall induction." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3693086" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3693086/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="221">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). They are characterized as a round, redbrownish spot around the gall initiation site. In these reactions, morphological and histological changes cause the death of the attacked tissue, which culminate in the localization, containment and death of the galling larvae (
<bibRefCitation id="52234B73FFF5031CFE6A2B3A57626754" author="Fernandes, G. W. &amp; Negreiros, D." box="[450,771,1347,1366]" journalOrPublisher="Ecol. Entomol." pageId="1" pageNumber="221" pagination="46 - 55" part="26" refId="ref3039" refString="Fernandes, G. W., Negreiros, D., 2001. The occurrence and effectiveness of hypersensitive reaction against galling herbivores across host taxa. Ecol. Entomol. 26, 46 - 55." title="The occurrence and effectiveness of hypersensitive reaction against galling herbivores across host taxa" type="journal article" year="2001">
Fernandes and Negreiros, 
<date id="420C1042FFF5031CFD782B3A57626754" box="[720,771,1347,1366]" pageId="1" pageNumber="221" value="2001">2001</date>
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="52234B73FFF5031CFFDA2B2655386770" author="Fernandes, G. W. &amp; Duarte, H. M. &amp; Luttge, U." box="[114,345,1375,1394]" journalOrPublisher="Trees" pageId="1" pageNumber="221" pagination="407 - 411" part="17" refId="ref3077" refString="Fernandes, G. W., Duarte, H. M., Luttge, U., 2003. Hypersensitivity of Fagus sylvatica L. against leaf galling insects. Trees 17, 407 - 411." title="Hypersensitivity of Fagus sylvatica L. against leaf galling insects" type="journal article" year="2003">Fernandes et al. (2003)</bibRefCitation>
stressed the importance of the hypersensitivity reaction, a mechanism by which the host plant identifies the attacked site, eliminates attempts to gall induction and protects itself against these insects.
</paragraph>
